Here's the thing nobody's telling you straight, so I'll do it.

You're not lost because you don't know enough. You know plenty. You've heard the verses. You've heard the talks. You can quote half of Romans and you still can't get off your phone at 1am. The problem isn't information. The problem is that nobody around you is showing you what a man looks like when Scripture has actually gotten its hands on him. So you're stuck choosing between guys who scream about alpha frames and guys who apologize for existing. Neither one is what God made you for.

Let me give you the framework. Not ten commandments for the modern bro. The actual shape of what the Bible calls a righteous man, translated for the world you actually live in.

**A righteous man is a governed man.**

That's the whole thing in one line. Everything else is downstream.

Paul says in 1 Corinthians 9, "I discipline my body and keep it under control." Proverbs 25:28 — "A man without self-control is like a city broken into and left without walls." Read that one twice. A city without walls means anyone walks in. Anything walks in. The algorithm walks in. The girl in the gym shorts walks in. The 2am despair walks in. The career envy walks in. Whoever's loudest gets to live in your head rent-free because you never built the walls.

The world has sold you two false versions of manhood. One is feral — Tate, hookup culture, dominate-everything, no master but my appetites. That's not strength. That's a slave with a loud mouth. The other is domesticated — porn-fed, conflict-avoidant, agreeing with whoever's in front of you, soft hands, soft spine, no edge. That's also not what you're for.

The Bible's man is neither. He's *free*. And freedom in Scripture, get this, is not doing whatever you want. Freedom is being able to do what's right when it costs you. When the late-night urge hits and your body says yes and your phone is right there and nobody would know. The free man closes the laptop. Not because he's repressed. Because he's *governed*. He has a King, and the King isn't his crotch.

So that's the foundation. Now here's what it looks like Tuesday afternoon.

**He kills what's killing him.**

Romans 8:13. Colossians 3:5. Paul uses the word *put to death*. Not manage. Not balance. Not work on. Kill. Your generation has been trained to "be gentle with yourself" and "do the work" and a hundred other therapy-speak phrases that sound healthy and produce nothing. Scripture is more violent than that, and more honest. Lust, laziness, bitterness, cowardice, the version of you that scrolls instead of prays — those things don't get reformed. They get executed.

